'''Yokotsukayama Kofun''' (横塚山古墳) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kumagaya|ja|熊谷市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|埼玉県|12=draft|12=draft}}. It has the type of a {{ill|Zenpō-kōen-fun|en|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft|12=draft}} and was constructed on the {{ill|natural levee|ja|自然堤防|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Fukugawa River (Saitama)|ja|福川|12=draft|12=draft}}, a tributary of the {{ill|Tone River|en|利根川|12=draft|12=draft}}. Although the mound has been significantly detypeed due to {{ill|cultivation|ja|耕作|12=draft|12=draft}}, it remains the only zenpō-kōen-fun in Kumagaya and was Historic Site1 as a Municipal Historic Site on {{date|1969-09-11|wikilink=yes}}.

The kofun was excavated twice, in {{date|1971|wikilink=yes}} and {{date|1976|wikilink=yes}}, and {{ill|cylindrical haniwa|en|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|12=draft|12=draft}} were unearthed from the surrounding moat. The main burial chamber has not been investigated, but the kofun is estimated to date back to the late {{ill|5th century|en|5世紀|12=draft|12=draft}}.

In the surrounding fields, areas with no remaining mounds have yielded haniwa. Records from the {{ill|Taisho period|en|大正時代|12=draft|12=draft}} describe a circular tumulus referred to as "Kozuka," suggesting that Yokotsukayama Kofun may have once been part of a kofun group centered around it.

