'''Yokotsukayama Kofun''' (横塚山古墳) is a [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] located in [[:en:Kumagaya|Kumagaya]], [[:en:Saitama Prefecture|Saitama Prefecture]]. It has the type of a {{ill|Zenpō-kōen-fun|en|前方後円墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenpō-kōen-fun|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenpokoenfun|qq=}} and was constructed on the {{ill|natural levee|ja|自然堤防|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/natural levee|qq=|1=natural levee|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11268410}} of the {{ill|Fukugawa River (Saitama)|ja|福川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukugawa River (Saitama)|qq=|1=Fukugawa River (Saitama)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q16767264}}, a tributary of the {{ill|Tone River|en|利根川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tone River|qq=}}. Although the mound has been significantly detypeed due to {{ill|cultivation|ja|耕作|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/cultivation|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 農耕|1=farming|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q24886094}}, it remains the only zenpō-kōen-fun in Kumagaya and was Historic Site1 as a Municipal Historic Site on {{date|1969-09-11|wikilink=yes}}.

The kofun was excavated twice, in {{date|1971|wikilink=yes}} and {{date|1976|wikilink=yes}}, and {{ill|cylindrical haniwa|en|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/cylindrical haniwa|13=User:Immanuelle/Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=}} were unearthed from the surrounding moat. The main burial chamber has not been investigated, but the kofun is estimated to date back to the late {{ill|5th century|en|5世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/5th century|qq=}}.

In the surrounding fields, areas with no remaining mounds have yielded haniwa. Records from the {{ill|Taisho period|en|大正時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taisho period|qq=}} describe a circular tumulus referred to as "Kozuka," suggesting that Yokotsukayama Kofun may have once been part of a kofun group centered around it.

